"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934851","Treasury","false","2018-07-12","<p>The Ivory Bill will prevent the poaching of elephants by introducing a total ban, with narrow and limited exemptions, on sales in the UK that contribute directly or indirectly to the poaching of elephants.</p><p> </p><p>At present, sales of ivory by VAT registered businesses are subject to VAT under normal VAT rules. The Government’s assessment of the Ivory Bill’s impact on sales of ivory is available online at:</p><p> </p><p>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/710369/ivory-bill-ia.pdf</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-07-12T16:34:18.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934851/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934851/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-07-04","Ivory: Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the loss of revenue to the Exchequer as a result of the effect of the ivory ban set out in the Ivory Bill.","false","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne","160661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934852","Department for Transport","false","2018-07-09","<p>The Pedal Bicycles (Safety) Regulations 2010 require a bell to be fitted to an assembled bicycle at the point of sale, but there is currently no legal requirement for bicycles to be fitted with bells when in use on public roads or paths. Rule 66 of the Highway Code recommends that a bell should be fitted to all bicycles, and advises cyclists to be considerate of other road users, particularly blind and partially sighted pedestrians, and to use the bell where appropriate to signal to others that they are nearby.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has received representations from various stakeholders on this matter as part of the recent wide-ranging Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy Safety Review call for evidence. Some respondents have suggested changing the current legislation to require all bikes to be fitted with bells when in use. The Department is currently analysing the 13,000 or so responses to the call for evidence, and will announce next steps later this year. In considering the case for any change to the current legislation on bike bells, the Department will consider matters such as how effectively any new requirement could be enforced.</p><p> </p><p>The Pedal Bicycles (Safety) Regulations 2010 are primarily designed to ensure consumer protection at the point of sale, and they do not cover the use of bicycles. They were introduced following a consultation in 2009.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","160657 ; 160658 ; 160659 ; 160660","2018-07-09T10:32:55.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934852/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934852/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-07-04","Bicycles: Safety Measures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will conduct a public consultation on the (a) advantages and (b) disadvantages of making compulsory the equipping of bicycles with an effective auditory warning device whenever ridden on public roads or paths.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","160656"
