"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934220","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-07-11","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I provided to Question <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;use-dates=True&amp;uin=125593" target="_blank">125593</a> on 6 February 2018.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-07-11T16:38:22.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934220/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934220/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-07-03","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the annual cost to the public purse of universal credit childcare in the current spending review period.","false","Biography information for Tom Tugendhat","Tonbridge and Malling","Tom Tugendhat","160312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934221","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-06","<p>No data is held centrally on the number of women diagnosed with endometriosis.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-07-06T12:30:48.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934221/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934221/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-07-03","Endometriosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many women have been diagnosed with endometriosis in each of the last eight years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","160103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934222","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-09","<p>Local authorities have a range of powers to intervene where there is a risk to public saftey.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-07-09T16:39:57.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934222/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934222/answer","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934222/answer/previousversion/68089","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/members/4483","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934222/answer/previousversion/68089",,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-03","Land: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps local authorities may take to tackle public safety concerns on unregistered land.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","160179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934223","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-07-06","<p>Under Universal Credit, the online digital account is fundamental to the design, which allows claimants access to all their personal, medical, financial and other data. As a result, the claimant ‘holds the key’ to that account at all times. Running a system of implied consent in Universal Credit means that the risk of disclosure of this material to third parties is heightened beyond an acceptable level under the data protection rules and might also undermine some of the other security features we build into the system through personal accreditation.</p><p> </p><p>A claimant can, however, give explicit consent for an adviser or other third party to talk to the Department about their Universal Credit claim via their journal, over the phone or in person, when accompanied by their adviser, and can state what information can be shared, with whom and for what purpose. Alternatively, if a personal appointee is appropriate, the claimant or appointee can raise this at the initial claim stage and we can arrange a home visit to verify the appointee, which will enable them to manage the account for the claimant.</p><p> </p><p>We continuously review the service for vulnerable people who claim Universal Credit to ensure that it is accessible and responsive to their needs.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-07-06T12:55:25.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934223/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934223/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-07-03","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the effect of the removal of implicit consent in welfare cases on claimants with (a) learning difficulties, (b) mental health issues and (c) those for whom English is not a first language.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","160288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934224","Home Office","false","2018-07-06","<p>As the Home Secretary announced on 19 June, the Government is undertaking a two-phase review looking at the scheduling of cannabis. Part one was led by Professor Dame Sally Davies, the Chief Medical Advisor to the Government, and considered evidence for the medicinal and therapeutic benefits of cannabis and cannabis based medicinal products. This part of the review is now complete and the report was published on 3 July. <br>Also on 3 July, the Home Secretary commissioned the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs (ACMD) to undertake part two of the review which will consider the appropriate schedule for cannabis related products, based on the balance of harms and public health requirements. The government has asked for short-term advice within three weeks of the commission with a full review expected by July 2019.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","160292","2018-07-06T12:52:50.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934224/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934224/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-03","Cannabis: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to his Department's press release of 19 June 2018, Home Office launches review into medical use of cannabis, what the timetable is for the conclusion of (a) part 1 and (b) part 2 of the review into medical cannabis.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","160289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934225","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-06","<p>The Government has confirmed that when we bring forward the vote on the final deal, we will ensure that Parliament is presented with the appropriate analysis to make an informed decision.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to securing a deal that works for the entire United Kingdom - for Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland and all parts of England, including Greater Manchester.</p><p> </p><p>Ministers from across Government have carried out extensive engagement on EU exit - with businesses and industry bodies from all sectors of the economy and all regions of the UK, with civil society groups including consumer bodies, trade unions, charities and academia, and with the Mayor of Greater Manchester and other Combined Local Authorities.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2018-07-06T15:45:59.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934225/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934225/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-03","Economic Situation: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will publish the Government's impact assessment of the effect on economy of Greater Manchester of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","160290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934226","Department for Education","false","2018-07-06","<p>Schools in Manchester were allocated £43.2 million through the pupil premium in 2017-18 and £43.4 million in 2018-19.[1] [2] The pupil premium targets funding at pupils from the most deprived backgrounds to help them achieve their full potential.</p><p>In 2017-18, schools in Manchester were allocated £5,281 per pupil through the schools block of the Dedicated Schools Grant (DSG). The average per pupil funding for England as a whole was £4,619 per pupil.[3]</p><p>In 2018-19, schools in Manchester were allocated £5,267 per pupil through the schools block of the DSG. The average per pupil funding for England as a whole was £4,630 per pupil.[4]</p><p>The figures for the two years are not comparable. In 2018-19 the Department created the central school services block, which was previously in the schools block. This is given to local authorities so that they can provide central services for schools.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Full details of Pupil Premium in 2017-18 can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-conditions-of-grant-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-conditions-of-grant-2017-to-2018</a>.</p><p>[2] Full details of Pupil Premium in 2018-19 can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-conditions-of-grant-2018-to-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-conditions-of-grant-2018-to-2019</a>.</p><p>[3] Full details of the DSG in 2017-18 can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018</a>.</p><p>[4] Full details of the DSG in 2018-19 can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2018-to-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2018-to-2019</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-07-06T16:14:10.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934226/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934226/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934226/answer/previousversion/68141","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/members/111","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934226/answer/previousversion/68141",,,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-03","Schools: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the funding for schools in Manchester in (a) 2017-18 and (b) 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","160291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934227","Home Office","false","2018-07-06","<p>As the Home Secretary announced on 19 June, the Government is undertaking a two-phase review looking at the scheduling of cannabis. Part one was led by Professor Dame Sally Davies, the Chief Medical Advisor to the Government, and considered evidence for the medicinal and therapeutic benefits of cannabis and cannabis based medicinal products. This part of the review is now complete and the report was published on 3 July. <br>Also on 3 July, the Home Secretary commissioned the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs (ACMD) to undertake part two of the review which will consider the appropriate schedule for cannabis related products, based on the balance of harms and public health requirements. The government has asked for short-term advice within three weeks of the commission with a full review expected by July 2019.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","160289","2018-07-06T12:52:50.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934227/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934227/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-03","Cannabis: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to his Department's press release of 19 June 2018, Home Office launches review into medical use of cannabis, when the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs will begin part two of the review.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","160292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934228","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-06","<p>We published guidance on 3 July setting out how local authorities and housing associations can apply for funding for the replacement of unsafe Aluminium Composite Material cladding on social residential buildings 18 metres and over. We want to be able to make payments as soon as possible so would like building owners to make applications by the end of August.</p><p>The application guidance is available at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/social-sector-acm-cladding-remediation-fund-application-guidance" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/social-sector-acm-cladding-remediation-fund-application-guidance</a>.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-07-06T11:33:21.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934228/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934228/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-03","High Rise Flats: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many (a) local authorities and (b) housing associations have (i) applied for and (ii) been granted funding for the replacement of flammable cladding on tower blocks; and how many (A) local authority and (B) housing association tower blocks have been (1) the subject of such applications and (2) been granted that funding.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","160072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934229","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-06","<p>Grant funding will be available to cover all reasonable costs for the remediation of Aluminium Composite Material cladding systems which have failed large-scale fire performance tests commissioned by Government in 2017 on social housing buildings 18 metres and over owned by local authorities and housing associations. From initial information provided by social landlords, the Government estimates the total costs to be £400 million.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-07-06T11:32:39.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934229/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934229/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-03","High Rise Flats: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to his Department of funding the replacement of cladding on local authority and housing association tower blocks.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","160073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934230","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-07-11","<p>The Offender Management in Custody (OMiC) operating model is currently being rolled out across the prison estate. Roll-out of key workers, who will conduct these sessions, has commenced in 42 prisons to date with 6 prisons having fully rolled out. We are closely monitoring staff recruitment, key worker training, development of implementation plans and delivery of key worker sessions at each site via monthly data returns, and key workers are required to make an entry on NOMIS following each key worker session, that are monitored for data quantity and quality.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","160325 ; 160326","2018-07-11T16:15:53.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934230/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934230/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-07-03","Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister of State for Justice of 2 July 2018, Official Report, column 100, in how many prisons the system of weekly 45 minute individual meetings between prisoners and prison officers has started.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","160323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934231","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-07-06","<p>Full roll-out of key workers in closed prisons will take place as part of the Offender Management in Custody (OMiC) model and is planned to be completed by 30 June 2019.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-07-06T13:59:57.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934231/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934231/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-07-03","Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister of State for Justice of 2 July 2018, Official Report, column 100, whether he has a target date for the system of weekly 45 minute individual meetings between prisoners and prison officers to be in operation in all prisons.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","160324"
